    <stitle>FRONT DRIVE AXLE WHEEL ENDS: FABCO SDA-12 - ADJUSTMENTS - DRAG LINK</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc id="hl0201012" svcproctype="adjust" graphiccount="1">
        <title>DRAG LINK</title>
        <para>Most installations have vertical socket ends (refer to
            <hotlnk xrefid="f0201017">Figure 17</hotlnk>) which are similar in construction to the tie rod.
        </para>
        <figure id="f0201017" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figg02/g0201017.webp" type="webp"/>
            <caption>Figure 17. Typical Drag Link End</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1>1. DRAG LINK</callout1>
                <callout1>2. BALL STUD</callout1>
                <callout1>3. BALL SOCKET ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                <callout1>4. SPRING</callout1>
                <callout1>5. PITMAN ARM</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <para>
            <emph type="bold">Replacement Criteria</emph>
            - the drag link must be free to rotate within the ball stud socket. Replace the drag link if it moves more
            than 1/16 of an inch in the axial direction (
            <hotlnk document="s02010_7.xml" xrefid="f0201015">Figure 15</hotlnk>) when measured on-vehicle.
            <emph type="bold">Do not pry</emph>
            on steering linkages with a bar as damage may result.
        </para>
        <para>An alternate method of evaluating the drag link is by rotating the ball stud with the stud removed from
            the steering arm. Torque to rotate the stud in the end cap should be 5.0 in-lbs. (0.565 N&#183;m) or more (
            <hotlnk document="s02010_7.xml" xrefid="f0201016">Figure 16</hotlnk>).
        </para>
    </svcproc>
